## Conventions

- **Module docstring:** Every `.py` file starts with a one-line `"""..."""` module docstring.
- **Section dividers:** Group related top-level definitions (exceptions, helpers, classes) with `# ---...` banner comments containing a short label (e.g. `# Exception`, `# Backlog helpers`).
- **Class method grouping:** Inside a class, use `# -- Label ---...` inline banners to separate logical groups of methods (e.g. `# -- Backlog fetch ---`, `# -- Work order PATCH ---`). Shared infra methods come first, then public methods grouped by feature.
- **Docstrings:** Public functions/methods get a concise one-line docstring. Private helpers (`_`-prefixed) get a docstring only when the intent is non-obvious. Do not add docstrings that repeat the function name or signature.
- **No narration comments:** Do not add inline comments that restate what the code does. Comments should explain *why*, not *what*.
- **Import order:** stdlib, blank line, third-party, blank line, local app imports.

## Things to avoid

- Defensive programming unless absolutely necessary, deep nesting, and over-engineering when a simple path suffices.
